team_synopses.1: Kyren Williams in Round 4 was the lone bright spot in this trainwreck, delivering 202.9 points as a workhorse RB1 when Will actually needed him to be. Mark Andrews in Round 13 looked like theft at the time, but his 12.3 points and season-ending injury turned a potential league-winning steal into a roster-clogging disaster that perfectly summarized this D-grade debacle.
team_synopses.2: Snagging Travis Kelce in Round 13 was highway robbery—a 4.5-star tight end who delivered 164.8 points is the kind of value that wins leagues, not salvages disasters. But burning a 9th rounder on Calvin Ridley's measly 19.1 points and 0.5-star stink bomb? That's the kind of catastrophic whiff that turns "playoff contender" into "mathematical elimination by Week 10."
team_synopses.3: Snagging De'Von Achane in Round 2 was highway robbery—his 271.9 points and 4.0-star rating carried this mediocre roster harder than a pack mule in the Grand Canyon. Burning a Round 16 pick on Player -1, who delivered a goose egg with a 1.0-star rating, is the kind of roster clog that turns "playoff hopeful" into "mathematical elimination by Week 10."
team_synopses.5: Lou Chrisos absolutely robbed everyone blind by snagging Jaxon Smith-Njigba in Round 11, turning a mid-draft flier into a 5-star, 287.4-point monster who delivered WR1 production at a WR4 price. The only blemish on this A+ masterpiece was burning a 15th rounder on Kyle Williams, who managed a pathetic 2.2 points with his 0.5-star performance—though honestly, that late in the draft, you're basically throwing darts at a bar anyway.
team_synopses.6: Allan Baut's lone bright spot was snagging Jahmyr Gibbs in Round 1, who delivered 307.6 points of explosive dual-threat production that single-handedly kept this C- draft from complete disaster. The real backbreaker was burning a Round 16 pick on Player 3917232, who posted a perfect 0.0 points—because apparently Allan thought roster spots grow on trees.
team_synopses.7: Alex Pandolfi absolutely robbed their league by snagging Patrick Mahomes in Round 7, riding his 272.62 points and 5.0-star dominance to fantasy glory while everyone else reached for running backs like suckers. Meanwhile, burning a 15th rounder on Najee Harris's pathetic 11.6-point season (0.5 stars) was like drafting a traffic cone, though at that point in the draft, even a terrible pick couldn't sink this A-grade masterpiece.
team_synopses.8: Noah Ip's first-round gamble on Christian McCaffrey (Rd 1) paid off spectacularly with 328.5 points of elite RB1 production, proving that when healthy, CMC is still the cheat code of fantasy football. Meanwhile, burning a 10th-round pick on Kaleb Johnson delivered a whopping -0.2 points—somehow finding one of the few players who actually cost you points is almost impressive in its own terrible way.
team_synopses.9: Snagging Bijan Robinson in Round 1 was the lone bright spot in Will's draft, as the dynamic RB1 delivered exactly what you'd expect with 264.3 points and 4.0-star production that carried this mediocre roster. Burning a 16th-rounder on Luther Burden III—a wide receiver who mustered a pathetic 2.2 points and 0.5-star rating—perfectly encapsulates the kind of speculative garbage that dragged Will's draft grade down to a B-.
